ct9ZlCYD1ly9joG4dLuo9a1vUuq3nViY5ODPhE=\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating Maven Dependencies**\\n\\nI’m considering whether we need an extra dependency for the Basic manager. I’m thinking that if I use Plexus IOC, maybe the maven-scm-manager-plexus isn’t really necessary. I should inspect the dependency tree from the pom file to check on version 2.0. I wonder if the dependency on javax.inject for maven-scm-provider-gitexe 2.0 is used inherently. I’ll also need some guidance on API changes to avoid conflicts.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Deciding on Setup Options**\\n\\nI’m considering whether to set up beyond the regular generated scaffold before full coverage is possible. Maybe I could return a no_action response along with agent guidance? If there’s no deterministic setup, guidance for API changes could still be useful. I think I need to decide on including an advisory_preparation if needed. They specified that I should only decide if more setup is necessary; if not, I should keep it simple and return no_action.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering Guidance for Git Setup**\\n\\nI’m thinking it might be useful, even though it's not deterministic. I must remember not to restate deterministic entries as guidance since there aren’t any. However, if I end up with a no_action response, empty guidance might be appropriate. I should thoroughly research whether the documentation requires a git binary setup. I know the \\\"git executable\\\" implementation relies on the installed version of git, so I’ll need to clarify that in my guidance.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering git execution in testing**\\n\\nAlright, I'm exploring the execution of commands in a local environment, not Docker. For tests involving git commands, it's crucial that the local git binary is available and configured with global user information. While existing tests avoid executing commits, achieving meaningful test coverage could involve parsing and command construction. However, for Maven SCM, if a commit is generated, I might need to set environment variables for user identity properly. If this is neglected, the git executable will fail during integrations.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating git configuration for tests**\\n\\nI'm considering the setup choices for running tests that execute git commits in a temporary repository. It seems I might need to configure the git identity there, but it’s not strictly necessary. To properly call `checkIn`, the identity must be set, although I could avoid this check or configure the repository directly in the test code. I might need to look at upstream tests for any prerequisites, especially for maven-scm git tests that work with local repositories without Docker. It's worth inspecting the source jar for better insights!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_QAkGiXsSg1EbcHFG0Dzs8Gsy|fc_0f71aa7f4ac1cdd2016a294c0cfc1c8194b77ec05f27c02b5e", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "tmp=$(mktemp -d)\npython3 - <<'PY' \"$tmp\"\nimport sys, urllib.request, os\nfor art in ['maven-scm-provider-gitexe','maven-scm-provider-gittest','maven-scm-test']:\n for cls in ['-sources.jar','.jar']:\n  url=f'https://repo1.maven.org/maven2/org/apache/maven/scm/{art}/2.0.0/{art}-2.0.0{cls if cls.startswith(\"-\") else \"\"}'\nPY\n# simpler\npython3 - <<'PY' \"$tmp\"\nimport urllib.request, os, sys\nfor art in ['maven-scm-provider-gitexe','maven-scm-provider-gittest','maven-scm-test']:\n url=f'https://repo1.maven.org/maven2/org/apache/maven/scm/{art}/2.0.0/{art}-2.0.0-sources.jar'\n try:\n  p=os.path.join(sys.argv[1],art+'-sources.jar'); urllib.request.urlretrieve(url,p); print(p)\n except Exception as e: print('ERR',url,e)\nPY\nfor j in \"$tmp\"/*sources.jar; do echo \"--- $(basename $j)\"; jar tf \"$j\" | grep -E 'Test.java|Git.*Command|Abstract.*Tck|ScmTestCase' | head -80; done", "timeout": 60}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "O